# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: national-historic-landmark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The building occupies the site of the Majestic Building, which was demolished in 1962 to make way for 1001 Woodward.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] It was constructed between 1963 and 1965 to house headquarters for First Federal Savings and Loan of Detroit, and was known as the **First Federal Building**.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] By January 1998, the Savings and Loan was part of Charter One Financial and the parent company sought to sell the structure and lease a portion back.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In December of that year, it was purchased by a partnership of The Carpenters Pension Trust Fund-Detroit & Vicinity and the Operating Engineers Local 324 Pension Fund for $6.5 million.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] As part of the sale, Charter One leased the ground floor, two office floors and the basement.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The Michigan Court of Appeals occupied two floors under a lease which ended in 2001.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The court relocated to Cadillac Place with several other State of Michigan offices.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In March 1999, the pension fund partnership announced a $15 million renovation of the building and a new name, **Woodward Plaza**.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] They also planned to convert the upper floors to luxury condominiums.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The pension fund partnership sold the building to Sky Development in April 1994 after spending $20 million on renovations.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] Sky Development also purchased an adjacent parcel behind the building to construct a parking garage.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] Sky Development continued the pension funds' plan to convert part of the building into 144 residential units, however this plan collapsed at the end of 2007 and ownership reverted to the pension funds.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The building and adjacent parking garage were subsequently purchased by Greektown business owner Dimitrios Papas in January 2008 and renovations were completed.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In May 2010, GalaxE Solutions systems signed a lease for 28,000 square feet (2,600 m2) bringing the occupancy to 25 percent.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In September 2010, GalaxE leased an additional 12,000 square feet (1,100 m2).
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In March 2013, Rock Ventures, the umbrella company of Dan Gilbert's business including Quicken Loans, announced its purchase of the building.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] Quicken Loans subsequently moved its mortgage servicing group into the top four floors.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places on December 11, 2013.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] It was nominated under Criterion A for its role in a 1950–1960s building boom and Criterion C for its architectural significance.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The building was designed by Smith, Hinchman & Grylls in the International Style.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The exterior façade is composed of tinted windows set precast frames covered with charcoal-gray granite.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The frames project from the façade creating a grid design similar to nearby 211 West Fort Street.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The structure is composed of two rectangular towers set at a right-angle and joined by an elevator-utility core covered in glass and matching gray granite.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] This arrangement of the towers help it make the best use of its irregularly shaped lot.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] Floors 24 and 25 house mechanical equipment and the two-story ground floor originally housed a banking room and convenience store.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] The floors and interior lobby walls were originally faced with white marble.
[src:national-historic-landmark/1001-woodward] In 1967, the building's architectural firm received an Honor Award from the American Institute of Architects for the design.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The **Albert Kahn House** is in Midtown Detroit, Michigan, within the Brush Park district.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] It is currently the headquarters of the Detroit Urban League.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The house was designated a Michigan State Historic Site in 1971 and listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1972.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] In 1906, architect Albert Kahn built a home for his personal use in Brush Park.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] In 1921, Kahn added a bathroom to the master suite.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] In 1928, as his business and social connections grew, Kahn added a wing to house his library and art collection.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] Albert Kahn lived in the home from 1906 until his death in 1942.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The Detroit Urban League obtained the building two years later.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] They continue to use it for their offices.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] Kahn's home is a two-story English Renaissance house, but with modern look.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The first story is clad in brick with a gray stone trim.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The second story is stuccoed, and the roof is slate.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The materials in the facade stress horizontal lines, while a group of windows emphasize the vertical.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] Two gabled dormers interrupt the roofline on the front of the home.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] A stone arch surrounds the Mack Avenue entrance, and is elaborately carved with Kahn's own floral design.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The house is soundproof and fireproof, with each floor constructed of reinforced concrete with wooden sleepers overtop, supporting the finished wood floors.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] On the first floor, the hall and dining room is finished in paneling, and the den is finished in half timber and half plaster.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] A kitchen and servant's room is also located on the first floor.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The second floor originally housed five bedrooms, two bathrooms and a sewing room; the 1921 renovation added a bathroom.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The attic originally contained an extra servant, but was later renovated to house two rooms and a bath.
[src:national-historic-landmark/albert-kahn-house] The 1928 expansion added a large gallery to the first floor, with a new garage behind, Over the gallery and garage are an additional guest bedroom, den and bath, and an additional servant's bed and bath.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The **Alden Park Towers** consists of a compound of four eight-story luxury apartment buildings located at 8100 East Jefferson Avenue along the Gold Coast in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] It is currently known as **Alden Towers**.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The collective of structures was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] Alden Park Towers consists of four eight-story buildings built from red brick with stone trim.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The buildings are interconnected at the first story; this level formerly housed commercial services such as grocery store and laundry.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The exterior is highly ornamented, with projecting bay windows extending from the ground to the roof.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The crenellated limestone at the roofline distinguishes these apartments from other similar buildings in Detroit.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The buildings originally held 352 apartments; the number is currently 389.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The Alden Park Towers were built in 1922 as the Berman Apartments.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] They were built south of Jefferson to take advantage of the natural beauty of the Detroit River.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] They were one of the few large apartment buildings built in Detroit.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] In 1971, the property was purchased for $6.5 million by Saperstein & Associates on a 40-year HUD-insured mortgage.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] In 2005, the property was almost sold at auction, but was pulled at the last minute when a $3 million debt on the mortgage was resolved.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] In 2012, Triton Properties acquired the historic Alden Park Towers property, located on Detroit's Gold Coast (the East Jefferson riverfront) out of foreclosure for $2 million, and began a $5 million plus renovation of all 382 apartment units in the four towers.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The project included renovation of common area, including a brand-new grand lobby with a large fireplace as the focal point, and a new fitness center with all-new equipment and flatscreen TVs.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The entire building is outfitted with free Wi-Fi.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] The grand lobby, designed with assistance from Sharon Carlile of Royal Oak's Italmoda, mimics the lobby of a modern boutique hotel.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] Additionally, major renovation to the property's riverfront was undertaken.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alden-park-towers] Renovation work was completed in the first quarter 2015.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The **Alexander Chapoton House** is a Queen Anne style row house located at 511 Beaubien Street in Downtown Detroit, Michigan.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places and designated a Michigan State Historic Site in 1980.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Alexander Chapoton was a descendant of one of the oldest Detroit families.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] His ancestor Jean Chapoton was a surgeon in the French army, and was assigned to Fort Pontchartrain, arriving in 1719.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Jean remained in Detroit until his death in 1762.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Years later, Jean's descendant Alexander Chapoton inherited his father Eustache's masonry business and a fortune to go along with it.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] He later expanded his business and became an important contractor in Detroit, helping to build several commercial blocks and residences, including the Globe Tobacco Building.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] He was the first Chairman of the Builders' and Traders' Exchange of Detroit (now known as the Construction Association of Michigan), serving 1885-1886.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] He also served on the Water Board and was appointed to a commission that selected an architect for the Michigan state capitol.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Chapoton's son, Alexander Jr., joined the family business and eventually inherited a greater fortune than his father had.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Chapoton built this house in the late 1870s as rental property.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] However, Chapoton himself lived in the home until his death in 1893.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The house is a three-story brick building with its foundation placed at the edge of the sidewalk.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The stone-faced basement raises the first floor several feet off the ground.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The facade is asymmetrical, with a three-bay first floor upper floors of differing height.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The brick and stone hoods over the windows vary from floor to floor.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] It is believed that the first and second stories were once separated by cast iron panels which were removed during renovation.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The interior floor plan is unusual, having space for Victorian Living hall.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The interior still retains the original trim, staircase and parlor fireplace.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] When this house was built, it was one of a row of similar homes on Beaubien.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] In the years following the house's construction, the area around it was cleared for commercial development.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The development was especially prevalent in the 1960s and 1970s; as a result, only a few row houses remain.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The Alexander Chapoton House is one of the last examples of Queen Anne style row houses in the city.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] The house was used as a rooming house for several decades.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] In the 1980s, it was purchased and renovated.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chapoton-house] Currently, the first floor is art gallery, studios are located in the basement and offices are on the upper floors.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The **Alexander Chêne House** was a private residence located at 2681 East Jefferson Avenue in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985 and designated a Michigan State Historic Site in 1986, but subsequently demolished in April 1991.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The Alexander Chêne House was a two-story, Federal-style house with additional Colonial Revival details on the facade, added after original construction.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The house was constructed of red brick sitting on a raised basement.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] A one-story porch sat in the center of the front facade, and the side walls rose above the roof to form fractables.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] A small cornice ran the width of the front.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The windows were topped with decorative iron lintels.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] A rear extension was added to the house in the 20th century.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The Chêne House was one of the few examples of the Federal style in Detroit.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] It was built in 1850 by Alexander Chêne on land which had been granted to the Chêne family by Louis XIV of France in 1707.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] Warren, who constructed the rear wing some time between 1902 and 1914.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The house was later used as a fraternity house for the University of Detroit, and during Prohibition was a speakeasy.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] Starting in 1935, the house was used as a fine dining restaurant, known as Little Harry's.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] The restaurant went through a series of owners, and closed in 1990.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alexander-chene-house] It was sold to singer Anita Baker, and in 1991, the structure was demolished and replaced with a franchise International House of Pancakes (IHOP).
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The **Alger Theater** is an historic neighborhood movie theater located at 16451 East Warren Avenue in the Morningside neighborhood of Detroit, Michigan.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] It is one of only two remaining intact and unchanged neighborhood theaters in the city of Detroit (the second being the Redford Theatre).
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2005.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Alger Theater, presumably named for Michigan governor Russell A.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] Alger, was built by Detroit theater developers Saul and Hattie Sloan, and designed by architect Charles Easton Allen.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Sloans leased the theater to Detroit theater magnate George Washington Trendle, and it first opened on August 22, 1935.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Alger was equipped with modern amenities such as the latest sound and projection equipment, comfortable seating, and air conditioning.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] It continued as a movie house for forty years.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] However, as the surrounding neighborhood suffered socioeconomic changes, attendance began dropping off.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] In the mid-nineteen seventies, ownership changed hands, and the theater was used for live performances and music in addition to movies.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] However, the theater closed its doors in 1981.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] In 1984, ownership changed hands again, and the Alger was re-opened as a B-movie house.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] However, profits were slim, and the theater closed again in less than a year.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] In 1986, the theater was purchased by Friends of the Alger Theater, a nonprofit community-based organization composed of neighborhood residents and businesses dedicated to preserving the Alger Theater.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] They are developing programming for the community while raising funds to restore and reopen the theater.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Alger sits at the corner of Warren Avenue and Outer Drive.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] It is constructed of structural steel faced with brick.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] A two-story square-plan tower structure with an instepped parapet stands at the corner, dominating the building's facade.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The tower houses the theater entrance and box office.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] A vertical sign with the theater's name extends from the tower toward the street.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] Along the Warren facade, four single-story commercial spaces faced with painted yellow brick line the sidewalk; the facade of the theater proper above is set back.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] On the interior of the theater, the inner and outer lobby and the balcony-less auditorium still show much of their historic finish.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The auditorium is constructed of concrete block with horizontal banding in smaller concrete brick; it originally sat 1182 people but now seats 825.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The stage was extended into the seating area to provide for theatrical performances.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] Stepped metal sconces with rounded ends adorn the walls.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Friends of the Alger Theater were awarded historic designations for the theater on the state, federal and local levels.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] In March 2009, the city's Historic Designation Advisory Board unanimously voted to recommend that the City Council approve the designation.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The Detroit City Council approved the formal local historic designation on Oct.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The state and federal designations were granted in 2005.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] Over the years The Friends have provided cultural opportunities and worked to build community by offering free programming in the surrounding neighborhoods.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] These have included theater arts classes at Detroit Public Schools, a neighborhood outdoor movie series, and many others.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] In 2014, the theater was surveyed for asbestos and underwent abatement, clearing a large barrier to restoration.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] As of 2025, the Alger has a new roof, restored storefronts, a rooftop deck on the East Warren side, an ADA compliant bathroom and an elevator.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alger-theater] The group is currently raising funds for full renovation of the theater.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] Alpha Phi Alpha was founded at Cornell University in 1906.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The organization was the first intercollegiate Greek-letter fraternity established for African American men.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The fraternity expanded, and by the 1910s a number of successful Alpha Phi Alpha brothers were living in Detroit.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The Gamma Lambda chapter of the fraternity was chartered on March 22, 1919.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] Over the next few decades, the chapter grew as more successful African Americans moved to the city.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The chapter met at various locations through the city, but did not have a permanent home.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The house at 293 Eliot Street was built in about 1912, and was first occupied by Herman and Lena Rosenthal.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] Herman died in 1929, and Lena remained in the house until about 1939, when it was purchased by the Gamma Lambda chapter of Alpha Phi Alpha.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The chapter used the house continuously until the present day, and it was the center of the social programs run by the fraternity.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The Alpha House is a two-story, rectangular brick building, built in a vernacular Craftsman style with a hipped roof and asymmetric facade.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The front façade has a partial-width elevated front porch, surrounded by a low brick wall with Tuscan columns and capped with a hipped roof.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] The porch is reached by a set of concrete steps, and two concrete steps that lead up to the upper end of the porch and the main entry.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] On the left side of the porch is a two-story bay window with double-hung windows; the other half has a box bay window on the second floor above the porch.
[src:national-historic-landmark/alpha-house-detroit] A hipped dormer projects above the roof in the center of the facade.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] A **National Historic Landmark** (**NHL**) is a building, district, object, site, or structure that is officially recognized by the United States government for its outstanding historical significance.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Only some 2,500, or roughly three percent, of over 90,000 places listed on the country's National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) are recognized as National Historic Landmarks.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] A National Historic Landmark District may include many contributing properties that are buildings, structures, sites or objects, and it may also include non-contributing properties.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Contributing properties may or may not also be separately listed as NHLs or on the NRHP.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] The origins of the first National Historic Landmark was a simple cedar post, placed by the Lewis and Clark Expedition on their 1804 outbound trek to the Pacific Ocean in commemoration of the death from natural causes of Sergeant Charles Floyd.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] The cedar plank was later replaced by a 100 ft (30 m) marble obelisk.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] The Sergeant Floyd Monument in Sioux City, Iowa, was officially designated on June 30, 1960.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Prior to 1935, efforts to preserve cultural heritage of national importance were made by piecemeal efforts of the United States Congress.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Over the following decades, surveys such as the Historic American Buildings Survey amassed information about culturally and architecturally significant properties in a program known as the Historic Sites Survey.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Most of the designations made under this legislation became National Historic Sites, although the first designation, made December 20, 1935, was for a National Memorial, the Gateway Arch National Park, then known as the Jefferson National Expansion Memorial, in St.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] The first National Historic Site designation was made for the Salem Maritime National Historic Site on March 17, 1938.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] In 1960, the National Park Service began administering the survey data gathered under this legislation, and the National Historic Landmark program began to take more formal shape.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] When the National Register of Historic Places was established in 1966, the National Historic Landmark program was encompassed within it, and rules and procedures for inclusion and designation were formalized.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Because listings (either on the National Register, or as an NHL) often triggered local preservation laws, legislation in 1980 amended the listing procedures to require owner agreement to the designations.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] On October 9, 1960, 92 places, properties, or districts were announced as eligible to be designated NHLs by U.S.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Agreements of owners or responsible parties were subsequently obtained, but all 92 have since been considered listed on that 1960 date.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] More than 2,500 NHLs have been designated.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Most, but not all, are in the United States.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] There are NHLs in all 50 states and the national capital of Washington, D.C.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Three states (Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, and New York) account for nearly 25 percent of the nation's NHLs.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Each of three cities within these states, Philadelphia, Boston, and New York City, has by itself more NHLs than 40 of the 50 states.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] New York City alone has more NHLs than all but five states: Virginia, California, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, and New York, the latter of which has the most NHLs of all 50 states.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] There are 74 NHLs in the District of Columbia.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Some NHLs are in U.S. commonwealths and territories, associated states, and foreign states.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] There are 15 in Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, and other U.S. commonwealths and territories; five in U.S.-associated states such as Micronesia; and one in Morocco.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Over 100 ships or shipwrecks have been designated as NHLs.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Approximately half of the National Historic Landmarks are privately owned.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] The National Historic Landmarks Program relies on suggestions for new designations from the National Park Service, which also assists in maintaining the landmarks.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] A friends' group of owners and managers, the National Historic Landmark Stewards Association, works to preserve, protect and promote National Historic Landmarks.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] If not already listed on the National Register of Historic Places, an NHL is automatically added to the Register upon designation; about three percent of Register listings are NHLs.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] Washington, D.C. is home to three specifically legislated exceptions to this rule: the White House, the United States Capitol, and the United States Supreme Court Building.
[src:national-historic-landmark/national-historic-landmark] All are designated as NHLs, but are not on the National Register.
